<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="469" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="74.[1392,2599,1958,2693]" pageId="74" pageNumber="469">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1393,1647,1958,1983]" pageId="74" pageNumber="469">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 64 mm, tail 36 mm, ear 8 mm, hindfoot 11-3 mm; weight 3 g. The Kongana Forest Shrew is small. Dorsum is brownish gray, and venter, limbs, tail, and ears are slightly paler. Ears are small, rounded, and covered with short hairs. Feet are pale, with elongated digits. Tail is ¢.56% of head-body length, pale brownish gray, and covered with short bristle hairs and a few longer bristle hairs on its basal one-half. There are four unicuspids.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="469" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="74.[1392,2599,1958,2693]" pageId="74" pageNumber="469">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1394,1504,2186,2219]" pageId="74" pageNumber="469">Habitat.</emphasis>
Apparently limited to patches of mixed and unlogged lowland tropical moist forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
